All kinds of cheese.

11:25.983 --> 11:27.983
Orange cheese, pizza cheese.

11:27.985 --> 11:30.185
I love all parts of pizzas,
especially the dough.

11:30.187 --> 11:33.354
Once I asked for a ball of
dough, and they gave it to me,

11:33.356 --> 11:35.656
and I took it to a park
and ate it.

11:35.658 --> 11:36.990
I'm so glad
you opened up.

11:36.992 --> 11:39.392
But then I realized
I needed some sauce...

11:39.394 --> 11:40.726
(laughter)

11:40.728 --> 11:43.395
People always make fun
of my eyes,

11:43.397 --> 11:45.397
but I guess they're...
Oh-ho! Good!

11:45.399 --> 11:46.931
Winston, can I
have a moment?

11:46.933 --> 11:48.632
(quietly):
Uh, yeah.

11:49.568 --> 11:52.035
I love Flip and Nan.
I hate Fred.

11:52.037 --> 11:53.269
No!
I know!

11:57.574 --> 11:58.739
So Fred's not shy,
he just sucks.

11:58.741 --> 12:00.240
When I asked him

12:00.242 --> 12:02.675
what his favorite hobby was,
he said, "Towels."

12:02.677 --> 12:05.744
I got to break up with that
human pile of saltine dust.

12:05.746 --> 12:07.378
I love Flip!
I mean, Flip taught me

12:07.380 --> 12:08.746
how to be vulnerable
with KC, you know?

12:08.748 --> 12:10.013
Yeah.
Nancy ear-candled me.

12:10.015 --> 12:12.181
I can hear for miles.

12:12.183 --> 12:13.749
Their relationship's
just such an inspiration,

12:13.751 --> 12:16.051
and I want to be around it,
but what can we do?

12:16.053 --> 12:17.585
We ditch Fred.
Forget about that dude.

12:17.587 --> 12:19.219
We establish
our own relationships

12:19.221 --> 12:20.787
with Flip and Nancy.

12:20.789 --> 12:23.222
Boom. Make future plans
with just them.

12:23.224 --> 12:24.790
"Future plans" is redundant,

12:24.792 --> 12:26.758
but other than that, I am on board!
Okay.

12:26.760 --> 12:29.193
Now, I'm gonna need some
alone time with Flip and Nancy.

12:29.195 --> 12:30.427
Can you stall Fred?

12:30.429 --> 12:31.594
Can I stall Fred?

12:31.596 --> 12:33.362
Of course I can stall Fred.

12:33.364 --> 12:35.597
I would do anything.
I love Flip and Nancy.

12:35.599 --> 12:37.599
Me, too! Are we totally crazy?

12:37.601 --> 12:39.067
Maybe! I don't even care!

12:39.069 --> 12:41.469
I don't even care, either.
Hmm.

12:41.471 --> 12:42.937
That's a vodka soda, I think.
(customers clamoring)

12:42.939 --> 12:44.571
Uh, it's close enough.

12:44.573 --> 12:46.739
I hear you! I'm getting to you!
Stop yelling at me!

12:46.741 --> 12:48.640
Shut up! I don't understand
what Cece's doing here.

12:48.642 --> 12:50.608
She led the walk-out.
If she's gonna be here,

12:50.610 --> 12:51.609
can she at least help us?!

12:51.611 --> 12:53.377
I am not gonna scab.

12:53.379 --> 12:54.778
Sorry, bae, I cannot scab,

12:54.780 --> 12:56.713
but I'm here for you
as your fiancée.

12:56.715 --> 12:58.748
You are my rock right now.
Do you need anything?

12:58.750 --> 13:00.382
No, I'm good, babe.
Okay, just let me know

13:00.384 --> 13:01.883
if you do. We are screwed!
MAN: Hey!

13:01.885 --> 13:04.452
Shut up! I'm trying my hardest!

13:04.454 --> 13:05.786
I shouldn't have fired Javier.

13:05.788 --> 13:07.654
I got to apologize.
This is all my fault.

13:07.656 --> 13:09.722
Obviously, this is your fault--
everybody knows that--

13:09.724 --> 13:10.823
but a boss never apologizes.

13:10.825 --> 13:12.057
It shows weakness.

13:12.059 --> 13:13.725
I feel like if Javier came back,

13:13.727 --> 13:15.426
the rest of the staff
would come back.

13:15.428 --> 13:17.294
That's a great idea.
I just said that.

13:17.296 --> 13:18.662
Such a great idea.

13:18.664 --> 13:21.798
Well, then give me one,
because I said it first.

13:21.800 --> 13:23.800
If you're giving it
for that idea,

13:23.802 --> 13:25.968
if it's about that idea,
then I deserve one.

13:25.970 --> 13:27.803
But I don't want one.

13:27.805 --> 13:28.637
And I felt left out.

13:28.639 --> 13:29.638
(clamoring continues)

13:29.640 --> 13:31.606
Shut up!

13:31.608 --> 13:33.674
Well, I wonder
what's taking them.

13:33.676 --> 13:36.243
Probably just the traff.
You know, the old 'ic.

13:36.245 --> 13:37.644
(both laugh)

13:37.646 --> 13:39.312
"The old 'ic."

13:39.314 --> 13:40.780
Anyway, I was thinking,
um, is there anything

13:40.782 --> 13:42.681
you guys like to do that
Fred doesn't like to do?

13:42.683 --> 13:44.816
'Cause I-I kind of...
I kind of just want

13:44.818 --> 13:46.818
to hang out with you
guys and not Fred.

13:47.821 --> 13:49.854
Hmm.

13:49.856 --> 13:52.323
Thank you for doing this,
by the way. This is great.

13:52.325 --> 13:53.490
Slow night.

13:53.492 --> 13:54.924
Just been
driving around,

13:54.926 --> 13:56.792
mouthing along
to hip-hop songs.

13:56.794 --> 13:59.127
Miss Officer, can we go?
I'm very hungry,

13:59.129 --> 14:00.828
and my possible
girlfriend and parents

14:00.830 --> 14:02.796
are waiting for us to order,
and it feels like

14:02.798 --> 14:04.130
you've done
over a million tests.

14:04.132 --> 14:05.998
That's what
I been saying!

14:06.000 --> 14:07.499
Where is the justice?

14:07.501 --> 14:09.434
You can go when
I tell you to go.

14:09.436 --> 14:11.636
Now, for your
next test...

14:11.638 --> 14:13.871
I want you to pretend
you're about to break-dance,

14:13.873 --> 14:16.273
but do not actually
break-dance.

14:16.275 --> 14:18.441
Break-dance-- that's it.
(Fred grumbling)

14:18.443 --> 14:19.442
I didn't mean...

14:19.444 --> 14:20.943
Buddy, I'm talk...

14:20.945 --> 14:22.511
Why would he take that
upon him...

14:22.513 --> 14:23.478
Don't ask.

14:23.480 --> 14:25.079
ALY:
I mean, whatever.

14:28.717 --> 14:30.216
Man, he's dumb!

14:30.218 --> 14:32.284
Give us more hands.

14:34.121 --> 14:35.720
Do it more animated.

14:35.722 --> 14:38.723
But less alive.

14:38.725 --> 14:40.057
That's pretty good.

14:40.059 --> 14:41.491
ALY:
Keep all of that,

14:41.493 --> 14:43.960
but pretend
you're underwater.

14:43.962 --> 14:45.695
Deeper.

14:46.864 --> 14:48.730
Deeper.

14:48.732 --> 14:50.498
Okay, Jess, uh,
what's going on here?

14:50.500 --> 14:51.499
Spill it.

14:51.501 --> 14:53.901
Well... (groans)

14:53.903 --> 14:56.370
it's just, you guys
are so amazing.

14:56.372 --> 14:57.971
And it's really rough out there,

14:57.973 --> 14:59.906
and it's nice to be
around something so great.

14:59.908 --> 15:03.175
And I-I'm not really
a love match with your son,

15:03.177 --> 15:08.512
but I think I might be in love
with you guys.

15:08.514 --> 15:09.913
(chuckles)

15:09.915 --> 15:12.382
Jess, we-we are glad
that you think that

15:12.384 --> 15:14.550
we're amazing.
Yes, we are.

15:14.552 --> 15:15.918
And we think that
you're amazing.

15:15.920 --> 15:18.320
Yes, we do.

15:18.322 --> 15:23.324
And, um... we know that
Fred isn't the best.

15:23.326 --> 15:24.758
We live with him.

15:24.760 --> 15:27.594
You know,
he can be so boring.

15:27.596 --> 15:30.597
I-It's like the apple
fell so far from the tree,

15:30.599 --> 15:32.098
it fell in a truck
Oh.

15:32.100 --> 15:33.866
and then disappeared
across state lines.

15:33.868 --> 15:36.368
(chuckles)
You guys are very honest.

15:36.370 --> 15:39.838
Did Fred ever tell you
that he loves model trains?

15:39.840 --> 15:42.607
Oh, those model trains.

15:42.609 --> 15:43.741
But he's your son.

15:43.743 --> 15:46.076
And we love him.
Deeply.

15:46.078 --> 15:50.713
And that's why we want
to make a deal with you.

15:50.715 --> 15:54.183
NANCY: You and Fred
equals you and us.

16:00.023 --> 16:01.555
Wow. L-Lovely home.

16:01.557 --> 16:02.756
Look, Javier,

16:02.758 --> 16:05.759
we've-we've come to give you
an incredible opportunity:

16:05.761 --> 16:08.862
for you to apologize
and get your job back.

16:08.864 --> 16:10.830
So, what do you say?

16:11.866 --> 16:13.098
(chuckles):
Okay, uh, well, Javier,

16:13.100 --> 16:15.100
let me tell you something.
Uh, I've been

16:15.102 --> 16:17.202
in the business world for
just shy of half of two decades,

16:17.204 --> 16:18.870
and I can tell you that
an opportunity like this

16:18.872 --> 16:21.606
does not come along
often, so...

16:22.542 --> 16:23.807
Your boss is extending his hand.

16:23.809 --> 16:25.141
Schmidt, stop.

16:25.143 --> 16:27.209
Look, Javier, I'm sorry.
I messed up.

16:27.211 --> 16:28.210
Nick, don't apologize.

16:28.212 --> 16:29.611
NICK: I've never
been a boss before,

16:29.613 --> 16:31.312
and it's weird, man.

16:31.314 --> 16:33.314
You're my friend, Javier.

16:33.316 --> 16:35.149
Remember when your
cousin was in town

16:35.151 --> 16:37.151
and-and my cousin was in town
and we kissed

16:37.153 --> 16:40.821
each other's cousins and...
then we peed on the ice maker?

16:40.823 --> 16:42.756
Yes. I remember that fondly.

16:42.758 --> 16:43.923
So rough.

16:43.925 --> 16:46.625
Look, we both chose
the bar over other stuff.

16:46.627 --> 16:50.061
I-I could've been a lawyer,
and-and you were a dentist.

16:50.063 --> 16:51.429
Were you really?
You were gonna be a dentist?

16:51.431 --> 16:52.897
Endodontist.

16:52.899 --> 16:54.431
Look, it's my job
to keep the bar open,

16:54.433 --> 16:57.901
but I still want it to be
a great place to work.

16:57.903 --> 17:00.270
If you come back,
that'll be my top priority.

17:00.272 --> 17:01.638
That and getting

17:01.640 --> 17:03.006
your old skanky cousin
back in town,

17:03.008 --> 17:05.008
so I could make out with her.

17:05.010 --> 17:08.011
And my skanky cousin
back in town,

17:08.013 --> 17:09.946
so you could make out with her.

17:09.948 --> 17:11.814
So what do you say?

17:11.816 --> 17:13.215
I say...

17:14.985 --> 17:16.284
...your mother.

17:16.286 --> 17:17.285
(chuckles)

17:17.287 --> 17:19.353
Your mother.
Your mother.

17:19.355 --> 17:20.587
Your mother!
Your mother!

17:20.589 --> 17:22.355
No, your mother!
(laughing)

17:22.357 --> 17:23.989
Ah, you son of a bitch.
I love you, man. Oh.

17:23.991 --> 17:25.590
You're the best, Nick.

17:25.592 --> 17:27.091
Yeah, you guys! Let's do it!
My hand...

17:27.093 --> 17:29.993
Next hand in, right? N...

17:29.995 --> 17:31.627
Okay, so you're saying
that if I date Fred

17:31.629 --> 17:34.096
that we can all
keep hanging out together.

17:34.098 --> 17:39.033
Yes. We don't want you to
lose us or for us to lose you.

17:39.035 --> 17:42.703
You're the child that
we always wanted to have.

17:42.705 --> 17:45.639
Imagine us as
grandparents.

17:45.641 --> 17:46.840
You think I haven't already?

17:46.842 --> 17:48.374
You'll learn to love Fred.

17:48.376 --> 17:49.875
And even better,

17:49.877 --> 17:51.877
you'll never have to go
on a first date again.

17:51.879 --> 17:53.879
Yeah. That sounds really good.

17:53.881 --> 17:56.047
There's no rush.
I mean, why don't

17:56.049 --> 17:59.016
we go up to the Vermont
house in the next few weeks

17:59.018 --> 18:00.884
and all be together?

18:00.886 --> 18:02.285
Vermont house?
Oh, yeah.

18:02.287 --> 18:03.686
It's an 18th century
farmhouse

18:03.688 --> 18:05.054
that we kind of
refurbished.

18:05.056 --> 18:06.822
Gah. Oh.

18:06.824 --> 18:09.891
We send romantic notes
on the clothesline.

18:09.893 --> 18:11.058
Oh, my geez.

18:11.060 --> 18:14.027
And a loom in the barn.

18:14.029 --> 18:15.628
(chuckles)
Poof.

18:15.630 --> 18:17.663
Hey, there!
Hi!

18:17.665 --> 18:19.231
(chuckling)

18:19.233 --> 18:20.732
WINSTON:
Right over here, buddy.

18:20.734 --> 18:22.633
I am terribly
sorry, you guys.

18:22.635 --> 18:24.635
We got held up
by an overzealous cop.

18:24.637 --> 18:26.637
Well, now, Fred, uh,
Jess was just saying

18:26.639 --> 18:28.338
how much she likes
model trains, right, Jess?

18:28.340 --> 18:31.040
FRED:
I didn't know you were

18:31.042 --> 18:32.074
a railie.

18:32.076 --> 18:33.708
That's so great.

18:33.710 --> 18:36.043
What's your gauge?
Are you a G gauge?

18:36.045 --> 18:39.212
Uh, G scale, gauge one?
HO scale? TT scale?

18:39.214 --> 18:41.347
Probably not
a tabletop girl, right?

18:41.349 --> 18:44.249
Do you do it costumed?
Or do you just do it leisurely?

18:44.251 --> 18:45.917
I deal mostly
with the, uh,

18:45.919 --> 18:48.519
transitional era,
post-Industrial Revolution.

18:48.521 --> 18:50.754
(groans)
I collect a lot of open-air

18:50.756 --> 18:52.088
coal engines.

18:52.090 --> 18:54.857
I'm the president of my
module group, actually.

18:54.859 --> 18:56.925
We use horn hook couplers,
so I'm kind of

18:56.927 --> 18:59.160
one of the best at
scenery building.

18:59.162 --> 19:02.663
Uh, just finished
this beautiful sanitation depot,

19:02.665 --> 19:04.097
made completely
out of balsa.

19:04.099 --> 19:06.866
I also was the first
to implement

19:06.868 --> 19:10.102
wire-framed humans, so that
the people are poseable.

19:10.104 --> 19:11.770
Station agent

19:11.772 --> 19:13.772
is now...
now he can bend his arm

19:13.774 --> 19:16.541
to say hello
as the train passes.

19:16.543 --> 19:19.043
There's one little girl
I use-- I call her Sally.

19:19.045 --> 19:21.678
I'm also quite good
at flocking snow,

19:21.680 --> 19:24.380
so I'm very popular
around the holidays.

19:24.382 --> 19:27.750
Ah! Stop! Please stop. I just,
uh... I ca... I can't do this.

19:27.752 --> 19:29.752
I can't believe I was even
considering doing this.

19:29.754 --> 19:31.553
I can't just settle
down to settle down.

19:31.555 --> 19:34.122
I really, really want you to
consider what you're giving up.

19:34.124 --> 19:38.092
Yeah, Terry Gross owns the
house next to us in Vermont.

19:38.094 --> 19:40.060
Oh, my God. Do you run into her
at syrup festivals?

19:40.062 --> 19:41.728
FRED:
We had a horse.

19:41.730 --> 19:43.129
Until it ran away.

19:43.131 --> 19:44.530
Its name was Daniel.

19:44.532 --> 19:46.198
Daniel Boulevard.

19:46.200 --> 19:48.133
I got to pick the last name,

19:48.135 --> 19:49.934
and I named him while
we were in the car.

19:49.936 --> 19:50.935
I have to go!

19:50.937 --> 19:52.069
Let's go.
Hey, listen,

19:52.071 --> 19:53.570
Jess and I really aren't
that close.

19:53.572 --> 19:56.205
I'm all about horses.
JESS: We're going!

19:56.207 --> 19:58.106
SCHMIDT:<i> You know what, Nick,</i>
<i> you were right.</i>

19:58.108 --> 19:59.907
A bar isn't just a place
of business.

19:59.909 --> 20:02.042
It's a place for people.
Mm.

20:02.044 --> 20:04.044
Which is something
I truly hate about it.

20:04.046 --> 20:05.545
Bunch of
bottom-feeders here.

20:05.547 --> 20:07.980
Chum at the bottom
of the ocean. Yuck.

20:07.982 --> 20:09.982
I know. And that's why,
as a manager,

20:09.984 --> 20:11.950
I'm thinking I have to fire you.

20:11.952 --> 20:14.986
Maybe you should fire me.
What do you think?

20:14.988 --> 20:17.121
You save enough money,
buy me out one day,

20:17.123 --> 20:19.790
you run this place
on your own.

20:19.792 --> 20:20.957
You really think I could?

20:20.959 --> 20:22.591
Yeah, definitely.

20:22.593 --> 20:24.392
I mean, your dumb bitch
of a mother sure could.

20:24.394 --> 20:25.960
What?

20:25.962 --> 20:28.128
Your-your mother, who, uh,

20:28.130 --> 20:30.630
we're referring to in this
circumstance as a dumb bitch.

20:30.632 --> 20:32.498
I think she could probably...
Wait, what?

20:32.500 --> 20:34.066
Come on. That's what you
and Javier do, right?

20:34.068 --> 20:35.434
C... Your... Uh, your mother,

20:35.436 --> 20:37.235
who, uh, you know,
is a dumb... is a dumb...

20:37.237 --> 20:39.003
Is that not...
is that not how the joke goes?

20:39.005 --> 20:40.070
(chuckles):
I know.

20:40.072 --> 20:41.237
Thanks, man.
Thank you.

20:41.239 --> 20:42.638
Um, can I have another napkin?

20:42.640 --> 20:45.073
Are you sure?
Uh, yeah, I don't need one.

20:47.010 --> 20:48.242
You know, look,
I know they turned out

20:48.244 --> 20:49.243
super weird and kind of like

20:49.245 --> 20:50.744
rich pimps, but...

20:50.746 --> 20:52.145
I just kind of miss 'em,
you know?

20:52.147 --> 20:55.148
I'm glad they were weird.
Kind of snapped me out of it.

20:55.150 --> 20:56.249
I was about
one park day away

20:56.251 --> 20:59.252
from a Vermont
model train-themed wedding.

20:59.254 --> 21:01.254
Yo, Nick,
you like my shirt?

21:01.256 --> 21:02.822
It look like I'm naked.

21:02.824 --> 21:03.989
Very cool, man.
(laughs)

21:03.991 --> 21:05.824
Right.
Come here, man.

21:05.826 --> 21:07.325
Hey, get out of here.
I'll catch up later.

21:07.327 --> 21:09.093
Boss man's got to go over the books.
Okay.

21:09.095 --> 21:11.428
Good to have you back, man.

21:14.766 --> 21:17.366
Oh, this is very terrible.

21:17.368 --> 21:19.000
♪ ♪

21:19.002 --> 21:20.267
I don't believe you.

21:23.171 --> 21:24.436
Can you put, like,

21:24.438 --> 21:25.537
a jazz spin on that?

21:29.008 --> 21:30.340
Look like an acorn.

21:30.342 --> 21:32.141
Start spinning.

21:32.143 --> 21:33.609
That's actually
pretty good.

21:33.611 --> 21:35.844
WINSTON: I just feel really
bad for Flip and Nancy.

21:35.846 --> 21:38.880
ALY:
<i> Shut up about Flip and Nancy.</i>

